  "title": "BCIT Mind Wandering",
  "description": "The BCIT Mind Wandering dataset comprises electroencephalography (EEG), eye tracking, and vehicle performance data collected during prolonged simulated driving tasks designed to assess fatigue-related biomarkers and driver performance. Participants performed 30-minute driving sessions under three audio conditions (task-relevant, non-task-relevant, and internal focus) while responding to vigilance targets and managing vehicle perturbations. This dataset extends prior driving research by incorporating extended time-on-task measurements and novel audio manipulations to investigate mind wandering and fatigue-induced performance changes.",
  "methods_description": "EEG was recorded using BioSemi 64-channel systems (plus 8 additional channels including 4 eye and 2 mastoid channels) at 2048 Hz sampling rate. Eye tracking was performed using Sensomotoric Instruments REDEYE250. Driving simulator data (steering wheel angle, lane position, heading error) were logged at 100 Hz. Participants completed a calibration driving task (15 minutes, steering only) followed by three counterbalanced 30-minute mind wandering conditions with different audio backgrounds. Lateral perturbations were applied to the vehicle, and participants performed a vigilance task identifying police vehicles. Subjective fatigue measures included Task-Induced Fatigue Scale (TIFS), Karolinska Sleepiness Scale (KSS), and Visual Analog Scale of Fatigue (VAS-F).",
